\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Grierson further develops the first principles of documentary in three points. The first point is that cinema has the ability to travel around. It can observe and choose from life itself. In short, film can be transported anywhere to shoot nature or society. For Grierson, this ability can be exploited in a new and fundamental art form (Grierson, 1971, p. 146). Next, original actors (or natives), as well as original scenes, can provide developed guides to a \'93screen interpretation of the modern world\'94 (Grierson, 1971, p. 147). What he means by this is documentary allows for an informative reflection or outlook on contemporary times. Thirdly, Grierson believes that stories extracted from the raw can be more satisfactory than the acted piece. In other words, documented moments captured can have a greater impact on the viewer than staged film. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 In Flaherty\'92s case, Grierson believes that Flaherty adhered to these principles, despite Hollywood\'92s desire to levy a ready-made living drama. Grierson thinks documentary must grasp its material right away, and come in intimacy to arranging it, mentioning how Flaherty would stay in the country and live with the people until the story was told \'92out of himself\'94 (Grierson, 1971, p. 148). Put differently, the documentaries form gave Flaherty the opportunity to present a more accurate view of his subjects by permitting him live in their country and shoot them directly. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 In Barsam\'92s book, he claims that a Flaherty work follows the 
\f1 realist tradition 
\f0 -- the necessity of cinematography over editing, Flaherty\'92s use of long takes, and dependence on long- focus lenses (Barsam1992, p. 53). Barsam also thinks that Flaherty\'92s work on 
\f1 Nanook 
\f0 taught him that the central style of the film should come from within the topic matter, by choosing the arrangement of information in realist film (1992, p. 54). Flaherty's exploration films had a great 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 influence on many other filmmakers, such as Merian C. Cooper and Ernest Schoedsack, who worked on two important travel films: 
\f1 Grass a Nation's Battle for Life 
\f0 (1925) and 
\f1 Chang 
\f0 (1927) \cb1 (Barsam, \cb3 1992, p. 54). One other filmmaker\'92s work that echoes Flaherty\'92s films is the Luis Bu\'f1uel movie, 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 (1932)\cb1 . 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Land Without Bread & Man with a Movie Camera\uc0\u8232 
\f0 In Caroline Francis\'92 article
\f1 , Slashing the Complacent Eye: \cb3 Luis Bu\'f1uel \cb1 and Surrealist 
\fs24 \

\fs32 Documentary, 
\f0 she argues that Flaherty, Cooper, and Schoedsack's movies were made to appeal to Western audiences (Francis, 2007, p.72). According to her, the films were highly manipulated through narration and editing. By way of contrast, \cb3 Bu\'f1uel's film, he joined ethnographic film conventions with those found in surrealist films (Francis, 2007, p. 73). Despite taking a surrealist approach, Bu\'f1uel used very few surreal visual aesthetics. Instead, 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 continuously used codes found in ethnographic films, in order to hide the film's cynicism and criticisms over the non-fiction genre. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The plot centers on the Las Hurdes area of Spain and follows the poor residents in La Alberqua. Using this area as the subject, Bu\'f1uel was able to incorporate his moral and political agenda in the film. Francis holds that the movie incorporates surrealism in three ways: the first is the film's usage of the surrealist instrument of black humor, the second is the film's criticism of Western bourgeoisie. Lastly, Bu\'f1uel interrogates ethnographic film\'92s control of logic when depicting reality (Francis, 2007, p. 83). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 With these set in place, Bu\'f1uel intentionally undermines his movie\'92s credibility in various ways. One example is using Johannes Bram\'92s Fourth Symphony synched to shots of the empty stares of the Hurdanos while he does a voice-over about the Hurdanos pitiful presence (Francis, 2007, p. 79). According to Francis, the narration was inconsiderate and unfeeling 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 10 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 11 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 because Bu\'f1uel wanted to imitate the viewpoint of self-content Westerners. Bu\'f1uel also wanted to use unconformable and shocking imagery (\cb1 Francis, \cb3 2007, p. 83). At one point in the film, a goat is shot, and a donkey is slaughtered. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 The main argument that Bu\'f1uel was trying to make with 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 is that since film is fundamentally a form of construction, ethnographic films tend to be about the filmmaker because it is the filmmaker that chooses how the stories are crafted, not the subject (Francis, 2007, p. 85). It should also be noted that 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 showed early signs that would be modernized by mock-documentary. The film fits into Roscoe and Hight\'92s degrees because it criticizes the medium of documentary by mimicking and displaying conventions from ethnographic and travelogue films to make a point. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Films like 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 challenge documentary techniques. For film critic Bill Nichols, these reflexive documentaries tackle issues of realism. One other example he provides is the 1929 movie 
\f1 The Man with a Movie Camera 
\f0 directed by Dziga Vertov. Nichols states that the film implements an analytic voice in order to explore the transformative ability of post- revolutionary Soviet society through the organized masses (Nichols, 2001, p. 90). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Vertov shows that the representation of reality is constructed by a cameraman (2001, p. 126). One scene Nichols mentions involves the cameraman riding in a car. The cameraman films people riding in a horse-drawn carriage next to the car. The movie then cuts to an editing room. Elizaveta Svilova, an editor and Vertov\'92s wife, is shown arranging the strips of film into the sequence previously seen (Nichols, 2001, p. 126-127). Nichols concludes that scenes like this review the notion of unhindered admission to reality. It induces the audience to think about the process of editing and the impression of reality made (2001, p. 127). 
