\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Newsreels and Television News 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Looking at other non-fiction films in the 1930s, the form known as 
\f1 newsreel 
\f0 became quite important over the next couple decades. Newsreel was short films that presented footage of actual events. The material offered eyewitnesses and graphic accounts of history (\cb1 Barsam\cb3 , 1992, p. 162). Newsreel also presented the material with simple and informative terms in a short amount of time. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 When crafting together newsreel pieces, it was common to separate bias from the subjects being discussed (though they approached subjects such as fashion with humor, or patriotism in sports). Within the decade, almost every theater showed a newsreel along with other programing, such as cartoons and two or more feature movies (\cb1 Barsam\cb3 , 1992, p. 162). There were even theaters that solely dedicated to showing newsreel. Newsreel soon became the source for screen and video journalism. Some major shows included The 
\f1 March of Time, Nykino's The World Today, 
\f0 and 
\f1 This is America 
\f0 (\cb1 Barsam\cb3 , 1992, p. 163). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 With television on the horizon, newsreel presented an example of how to handle visual news stories. By the late 1940s, television sales began to increase heavily. In reaction to these sales, the networks extended their evening broadcasts to seven days a week. Along with the longer schedules, the networks also began to run weeknight newscasts. NBC's news show premiered first in February 1948. Fox Movietone\'92s newsreel company produced the program and R.J. Reynolds sponsored it. The show had voice-overs but no on-screen anchors when it began. 
\f1 CBS Evening News, 
\f0 on the other hand, began in April 1948. It featured a cast of rotating anchors before Douglas Edwards became a regular (Ponce de Leon, 2015, p. 8). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 One important person CBS hired for its show was a journalist named Don Hewitt. He later became a producer for the network and made some notable changes to compensate for the 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 13 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 advantages and limitations of television (Ponce de Leon, 2015, p. 10). Hewitt formed the graphics art department to create charts, maps, and captions to better illustrate stories. He also brought in TelePrompTer machines, to make reading easier for anchors. (Before Hewitt introduced the machine, scripts were written on cue cards.) Hewitt was a major factor in CBS\'92 shift to 16mm film, and he began using in-house camera crews as well (Ponce de Leon, Ponce de Leon, 2015, p. 11). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Another area that Hewitt was responsible for was a paired-projector arrangement that blended narration with film. Essentially the system was used to create news package and served as an archetype for television news. The beginning of the story would have the reporter on camera, starting with a 
\f1 stand upper 
\f0 that announces the story. This section is followed by a voice-over, with the reporter's words recorded separately, detailing the piece. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Local stations also helped popularize the man-on-the-street interviews (Ponce de Leon, 2015, p. 8). With exceptions of those interviews, and the work of stations like 
\f1 KTLA 
\f0 or 
\f1 Telepix Newsree
\f0 l, most local stations gave summaries of wire-surface headlines. Rarely was much effort put into local stations, because most stations believed viewers got their local news from newspapers and radio stations. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 However, with cheaper equipment in the 1960s, such as video and microwave technology, local stations and network affiliates began to increase news programming (Ponce de Leon, 2015, p. 12). Throughout the 1960s many of these news conventions became the standard for the networks, allowing television to become a powerful tool for the public in U.S. It changed many institutions, including politics and sports. Some important topics networks covered at this time were the Great Debates between Kennedy and Nixon during the 1960 presidential campaign, as well as the civil rights movement (Brown, 1995, p. 275). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 14 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 News Aesthetics Replicated in Film 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 There are several examples where narrative film borrows newsreel and news broadcast conventions. Take for instance the 
\f1 March of Time 
\f0 newsreel from 
\f1 Citizen Kane 
\f0 (1941) (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 94). It provides the biography of Welles\'92 character, Kane, as well as information such as his death. In other movies, such as 
\f1 Night of the Living Dead 
\f0 (1968), fake news broadcasts provide information regarding authorities locally and nationally. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Fake news broadcasts serve a number of purposes in the films\'92 construction. The broadcasts are often used to help ground the narratives in a familiar social-historical framework. They can also be used to provide some commentary. With 
\f1 Living Dead
\f0 , the news is used as a parody of government and authoritative institutions, voices, and bureaucracy. The news bulletins also provide insight into the spread of ghouls (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 95). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Along with commentary, fake news broadcasts can show the significance of the visual medium to the people in the movie, demonstrate their reactions, and lend a sense of scale to events. The mock-documentary 
\f1 Cloverfield 
\f0 (2008) leverages fake news broadcasts in this way. When a giant monster attacks, the first thing the characters do is turn on CNN. At one point, the characters pass a shop window with news footage. This scene provides the first look at a whole shot of the monster, but the TV screen (viewed through the characters\'92 camera) is too small to show any big details of the creature. Here, the broadcast is used to ground the spectacle by showing it as a real news broadcast would in a case of a disaster or attack (North, 2010, p.84). Also in this movie, the news is treated as a developing story each time the characters pass a television, rather than simply inflating the image for exposition. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 With mock-documentary directly, television news codes can take up sections or entirety of a film\'92s stylistic framework. With 
\f1 Cloverfield, 
\f0 the characters are watching the news on 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 15 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 television. The news story is captured by a camera the character is holding next to the T.V. However, in the online advertising for the film, the various faux news reports exist independently as if the story was uploaded online by news networks. They show an oil rig collapse off the coast of Connecticut suggesting the monster from the movie is nearing New York City. In other films, news reports or television codes may be cut in the film to obtain the spirit of certain situations. In 
\f1 Best in Show
\f0 , for example, there is a dog competition. At points in the movie, the footage replicates codes from these types of televised events. Since the movie is made to look like a documentary, it gives the audience impression that the filmmakers obtained the footage of the competition from television network and spliced into their film.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 \cb3 Cin\'e9ma V\'e9rit\'e9 and Direct Cinema 
\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 The 16mm portable cameras were not only used by the news stations; the devices also opened the door for all-new modes of documentary representation in the 1960s. One such form allowed viewers the chance to observe the lived experiences of others\'92 day- to-day lives (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 235). Like the early \cb1 Lumi\'e8re shorts, these films would fit into the 
\f1 \cb3 observational mode 
\f0 (Nichols, 1994, p. 95). Unlike Vertov\'92s 
\f1 Man with the Camera
\f0 , which focused on Soviet life as a whole, cin\'e9ma v\'e9rit\'e9 and direct cinema moved toward shooting domestic and personal subjects. One pioneer of the style was Robert Drew. Drew formed a group at Time, Inc. with individuals such as fellow filmmaker Richard Leacock. Their purpose was to conduct experiments in mobile filmmaking and with synchronized sound shooting. \cb1 (Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 235). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 An important film they made was called 
\f1 Primary 
\f0 (1960), which followed U.S. Senators, John F. Kennedy and Hubert Humphrey, during their campaigning in Wisconsin for the Democratic presidential nomination (\cb1 Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 236-238). The movie showed speeches, 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 16 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 interviews, meetings, and motorcades. Drew was insistent that the filmmakers never ask or persuade any action for the subjects. Despite being rejected by all the big networks, 
\f1 Primary 
\f0 was broadcast several stations owned by Time, Inc. (\cb1 Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 238). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 According to Barsam in his book, 
\f1 Nonfiction Film: A Critical History, 
\f0 the techniques practiced during the decade became a fundamental part of T.V. reporting (Barsam, 1992, p. 281). Though not airing on ABC Network, ABC was impressed with Drew's group's work and contracted them to make documentary programming for them. Some films to come out of this include 
\f1 Yanki No! 
\f0 (1960) and 
\f1 The Chair 
\f0 (1963) (\cb1 Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 238). By the mid-1960's, the group began to scatter. Most of the filmmakers continued to use similar techniques in their own projects (\cb1 Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 240). One former member, Albert Maysles, went on to help direct the 
\f1 Salesman 
\f0 (1969). Unlike most documentaries for commercial television that dealt with high profile lives and performers, 
\f1 Salesman 
\f0 focused on four door-to-door Bible salesmen \cb1 (Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 241). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Though commercial television was at times hospitable for direct cinema, public and non- commercial television became a principal distribution for these types of documentaries, such as Fred Wiseman\'92s 
\f1 Titicut Follies 
\f0 (1967), 
\f1 High School 
\f0 (1968) and 
\f1 Welfare 
\f0 (1978) (\cb1 Barnouw, 1993, \cb3 p. 244). One thing that should be noted is that while direct cinema borrowed from cin\'e9ma v\'e9rit\'e9, they have different goals. According to Erik Barnouw\'92s book 
\f1 Documentary: a History of Non- Fiction Film
\f0 , cin\'e9ma v\'e9rit\'e9 is obligated to a paradox with simulated circumstances bringing truth to the surface, while direct cinema finds reality in the events that the camera records (\cb1 Barnouw, \cb3 1993, p. 255). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 17 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Reflexive and Performative Documentary 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 For many mock-documentaries, cin\'e9ma v\'e9rit\'e9 and direct cinema have become a target. Though the mock-documentary borrows the same style as these films, they are usually not categorized as such. Mock-documentaries are complete works of fiction and should not be analyzed under the same criteria as documentaries. What can be looked at is how they impact each other. Jane Roscoe and Craig Hight believe most mock-documentaries participate with observational and expositional elements, while the simulation of Nichols\'92 reflexive and performative documentaries supply extra-text associated with them (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. \cb1 21). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 According to Nichols, the purpose of the reflexive mode is to redirect the audience\'92s awareness toward the referential characteristics of the documentary rather than its formal qualities (1994, p. 93). Using reflexive procedures will not alienate the viewer from the film's techniques. Instead, the film guides the audience to look at the documentary\'92s subjectivities toward whatever topic it's representing (Nichols, 1994, p. 96). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Performative documentary, on the other hand, stresses the referential function as its main feature (Nichols, 1994, p. 94). As a result, it showcases subjective features directed at \'93classical objective discourse\'94 (Nichols, 1994, p. 95). Nichols also notes that the performative documentary can create a paradox. While the historical world is not forgotten, the film\'92s referential messages can establish a fiction through expressiveness, subjectivity, and stylization (1994, p. 98). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Roscoe and Hight praise the reflexive and performative modes\'92 ability to question the methods documentary uses to claim truth (2001, p. 36). However, they believe critiques are limited to these modes because they cannot separate from documentary\'92s foundations in 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 18 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 actuality. For them, mock-documentary can take the potential of the reflexive and performative modes and apply them to a methodical evaluation of documentary\'92s claim to truth (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 36).\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 \cb3 Different Forms of Mock-documentary 
\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Moving on, many mock-documentaries emulate the look of, and satirize popular culture in a manner akin to, observational documentary. For example, 
\f1 This is Spinal Tap 
\f0 (1984), makes use of material that came before it in the form of rock documentaries. Rock documentaries were a promotional tool for the music recording business to shed a sympathetic light on the subject or the filmmaker (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 119). Most of these were variations of direct cinema, such as the Maysles brothers 
\f1 Gimme Shelter 
\f0 (1970) with the Rolling Stones (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 119). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 What 
\f1 Spinal Tap 
\f0 attempted to do is criticize heavy metal bands, while also retaining an admiration for them. It engages the viewer with humor as well as relatable characters (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 121). The character development is much more in-focus than some previous mock-documentaries, like the made-for-T.V. film 
\f1 The Rutles 
\f0 (1978). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The Rutles 
\f0 was a series of skits poking fun at the mythology behind The Beatles (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 102). The characters in this film are much more of a representation of the public icons they signify than fleshed out individuals (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 104). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The handling of the observational form and characters has made 
\f1 This Is Spinal Tap 
\f0 a landmark mock-documentary film. Many filmmakers cite 
\f1 Spinal Tap 
\f0 as a reference point for their films, such as 
\f1 Fear of the Black Hat 
\f0 (1993) (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 121-125). Several televisions shows and movies have since used characteristics of the observational mode for mock-documentary storytelling such as 
\f1 The Office 
\f0 (2001-2003) (Griffin, 2008, p. 162). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 19 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 However, mock-documentary is not limited to a single mode. In early mock- documentary such as Woody Allen\'92s 
\f1 Take the Money and Run 
\f0 (1969) and his later effort 
\f1 Zelig 
\f0 (1983) he used the expositional mode. Both films use a narrator to voice-over events, highlighting the main character in stock footage and pictures. The films are also broken up in contemporary interviews of individuals that talk about Allen's character (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight\cb3 , 2001, p. 111). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Many mock-documentaries also use Nichols\'92 
\f1 participatory mode
\f0 , notably hoax films like 
\f1 The Blair Witch Project 
\f0 (1999). Nichols believes participatory documentary highlight the interaction \'93between the filmmaker and subject\'94 (Nichols, 2001, p. 34). \cb1 With 
\f1 Blair Witch, 
\f0 a group of film students are investigating the legend of the Blair Witch from Burkittsville. They interview residents of the area and read news articles. Both foreshadow events to come when they get lost in the woods (Prince, 2004, p. 197). For the movie, directors Daniel Myrick and Eduardo S\'e1nchez trained their three actors to use two cameras; the Hi8 camcorder and a 16mm camcorder. Most of the movie is shot through the character Heather\'92s Hi8. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 At the time, digital equipment such as the HI8 would lead to a revolution in filmmaking for no-budget filmmakers, due to its affordability and accessibility (Hopgood, 2006, p. 242). The new technology allowed filmmakers to sidestep conventional paths, such as formal funding sources (Hopgood, 2006, p. 243). The sound of the movie was almost always recorded from the mic on camera or on the character. In 
\f1 Blair Witch
\f0 , it was Michael\'92s DAT (digital audio tape) (Hopgood, 2006, p. 242). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 To further accomplish the 
\f1 reality effect 
\f0 Myrick and S\'e1nchez directed the actors to go into the woods for eight days and shoot. The cast used their real names and improvised most of their lines. At certain points, Myrick and S\'e1nchez left the cast alone in the woods and had the crew 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 follow the actors. The crew would scare them at night with various noises, and the directors rationed the amount of daily food the cast were allowed to have (Hopgood, 2006, p. 244). The techniques were inspired by US Army\'92s Special Forces to dive into parts of the psyche that are not normally touched (Hopgood, 2006, p. 244). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Like some of the other films listed, 
\f1 Blair Witch 
\f0 drew heavily from conventions of \cb3 cin\'e9ma v\'e9rit\'e9, observational documentary, and the direct cinema movement (Hopgood, 2006, p. 244). The result shared the movement\'92s values of rejecting practiced aesthetics of traditional cinema to create a close-feeling and immediate film. It should also be noted that 
\f1 Blair Witch 
\f0 displayed many aesthetical rules common to Dogme 95. Dogme 95 was a short avant-garde movement of film and video in Danish film production (Britt, 2013, p. 292). The Danish film director, Lars von Trier, first presented it in 1995 at the \'91Cinema in its Second Century\'92 conference in the Odeon Theatre in Paris. (Britt, 2013, p. 292) Attendees received a manifesto that outlined the movement. Some of the rules are \cb1 shooting must be done on location, the sound must never be produced apart from the images, or vice versa, the film must not contain superficial action (Britt, 2013, p. 293). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 The onset of Dogme 95 harkened back to cinema\'92s early roots, including Soviet cinema regulations and Lumi\'e8re film (Jess, 2005, p. 5). The goal of the movement was for filmmakers to cleanse themselves of mainstream movie practices in order to create films that exerted \'92pure\'91 cinema (Jess, 2005, p. 3). The challenges the manifesto presented encouraged filmmakers to discover inventive or older techniques, and to surpass them (Simons, 2008, p. 3). Take for example Von Trier\'92s film 
\f1 The Idiots 
\f0 (1998). In it, rarely were any shots predetermined. Instead, Trier pointed and shot the camera at presumably unscripted actors (Simons, 2008, p. 5). 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 20 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 While 
\f1 Blair Witch Project 
\f0 did not adhere to all the rules, it followed pretty closely to the manifesto, whether it was intended or not. For example, Blair Witch mainly used handheld footage and natural lighting. One answer for the similarities comes from the author, Dana Och, who believes that both types of films emerged during a neo-postmodern trend in the 1990s (Och, 2015, p. 202). According to her, was carried out through new, digital handheld aesthetics that Dogma 95 and 
\f1 Blair Witch 
\f0 followed closely. The result simulated a representation of veracity, helping challenge certain genre tropes (Och, 2015, p. 202). 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Modern Marketing and Promotion for Theatrical Mock-Documentary Releases 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Now that the significance of the historical and cultural development of documentary, news, and mock-documentary form is highlighted, it is important to briefly discuss the marketing of mock-documentary to mainstream audiences. 
\f1 The Blair Witch Project 
