\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The Degrees of Mock-documentary 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Unlike docudrama or documentaries, the mock-documentary is completely fictional (2001, p. 46). Roscoe and Hight categorize mock-documentary into three degrees: parody, critique and deconstruction (2001, p. 67). For example, the first degree, parody, is relatively 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 24 
\fs24 \

\fs29\fsmilli14667 25 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 tame in its criticisms toward documentary. The mock-documentaries primarily use the aesthetics for stylistic purposes, often aiming for humor (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 68). For example, in a degree-1 film, a silly situation might be taking place, only for the camera to turn toward someone who has a rational/deadpan face. Also, while documentaries are primarily used as a \'93call to action\'94, parodies frequently center their commentary on cultural figures, such as the movie 
\f1 This is Spinal Tap 
\f0 (1984). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 In this movie, the \'91documentary crew' follows the \'92band' in the same way they would an actual music group. In the movie the \'91band' has released albums and has gone on tour. These details create an 
\f1 extra-textual 
\f0 impression to audience of the bands \'91real existence' (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 69). Though it is likely the audience knows the movie is fake, they buy into the story because of the documentary style, as well because of the way the fabricated information reflects real cultural figures. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Degree 2: Critique mock-documentaries on the other hand, are deliberately reflexive toward factual discourse. A lot of times the subject matter includes or partially includes how media representations themselves are constructed. Looking at a documentary, the filmmakers often examine how the text is an approach for study, analysis, and investigation (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 69-70). One example, where we can see the mock-documentary used as a critique is the 1997 series premiere episode of 
\f1 ER
\f0 . In this episode a PBS film crew enters the emergency room to film a documentary. The episode presents itself as a critique of reality TV shows and their failure to follow moral principles of documentary texts (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, 2001, \cb3 p. 70). Another example is the movie 
\f1 Bob Roberts 
\f0 (1992) which criticizes the modern political process, particularly the American system of choosing candidates. It also argues that that 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 26 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 documentaries, as well as political satire, urge the audience to take action rather than accept the piece as a singular work of humor or information (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 71). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 According to the authors, the audience role with degree-2 mock-documentaries is to achieve differing measures of reflexivity toward parts of the documentary genre and popular culture. They also note that 
\f1 hoax 
\f0 films fall under degree-2 mock-documentary. With hoaxes, the text tries to confuse audiences about its authenticity. The result is that automatic interpretations are generated by the audience over the fictional status, even if the films do not contain meanings that are reflexive about \'92factual discourse\'91 (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 72). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 In other words, a hoax film is a fictional piece that presents itself as real. One example is the 1985 short horror film 
\f1 Devil's Experiment 
\f0 (1985). The movie is about three guys who kidnap a young woman and torture her in a variety of ways (McRoy, 2004). In order to add to its authenticity, the film begins with a black title card with scrolling text claiming that whoever was distributing the film obtained the video several years ago. In this way the film presents itself as \'92found footage,\'91 meaning the video was lost and later \'92obtained' at some point (McRoy, 2004). Like other mock-documentaries, 
\f1 Devil\'92s Experiment 
\f0 also used documentary codes such as handheld camera footage and long takes, along with natural lighting, to appear \'92real\'91 (McRoy, 2004). In order to pull off some of the special effects, there are carefully placed cuts during some of the acts. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Continuing to the third degree of mock-documentary, deconstruction, the main intention of these films is to critique set molds and expectations that surround traditional conventions of documentary and the capacity to document \'92truths\'91 (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 72). 
\f1 Man Bites Dog 
\f0 (1992) for instance, seeks to tear apart the political and ethical positions that documentary filmmakers take. Essentially the movie is about a film crew whose main focus is a serial killer. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 27 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 They follow him around but soon find themselves as accomplices and participants in his murders \cb1 (Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 74). The movie deconstructs the text on several levels, such as the value audiences expect from documentarians and censorship. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Another example the authors provides is 
\f1 David Holzman\'92s Diary 
\f0 (1965). The plot is about a filmmaker who wants to record his life and in the process discovers himself. The authors argue the main subject is not about the filmmaker\'92s life, but more about what the camera can do and record (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 74). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Degree 3 is the rarest form of text to use for mock-documentaries, likely because it is more specific to commenting on the documentary form, rather than on filmmakers or other subjects. For this reason, most mock-documentaries often fall under degree 1 and 2 (\cb1 Roscoe & Hight, \cb3 2001, p. 74).\cb1 \uc0\u8232 
\f1 \cb3 Nichols on Irony 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 Looking at Nichols (2001), he believes documentaries and mock-documentaries uses reflexive methods to bring the function of \'92representation\'91 into question ( p. 24.) It disrupts the assumption of documentary\'92s capacity to capture reality on film. One example he provides to illustrate documentary questioning itself is the film 
\f1 Land Without Bread
\f0 . Nichols reflects on a scene where the commentator stated that Hurdanos only eat goat meat when the goats accidently die. What the audience views instead is gun smoke floating in the corner of the frame as a goat falls off the mountainside (Nichols, 2001, p. 8-9). Nichols interprets the scene\'92s contradiction as a hint that Bu\'f1uel is not depicting a factual account of the Hurdanos culture. He believes that Bu\'f1uel uses irony to solidify the message not to believe everything we see and hear (Nichols, 2001, p. 9). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Nichols also refers to institutional framework as a possible way to define documentary. What he means by this is that organizations or institutions label their production as documentaries. In other words, we are told by an institution what we are seeing is documentary (Nichols, 2001, p. 22). Nichols uses shows on the Discovery Channel as an example. Since the Discovery Channel is devoted to showing documentary material, the shows are regarded as documentary unless proven differently. With mock-documentary, films like 
\f1 Spinal Tap 
\f0 take advantage of institutional frameworks to construct themselves in an 
\f1 ironic 
\f0 way (Nichols, 2001, p. 23). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Nichols writes that these films proclaim to be documentary, only to demonstrate that they are a forgery or imitation of documentary (2001, p. 23). For instance, 
\f1 The Blair Witch Project 
\f0 depends on using documentary conventions with the \'92gritty realism\'91 of camcorder equipment to sell historical believability of fictional events (Nichols, 2001, p. xii). Nichols mentions that if the audience takes the films\'92 self-descriptions sincerely, we will think Spinal Tap is a real rock band and Blair Witch is actual history. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 He writes that the statement is technically not wrong, but we may fail to understand that neither the witch nor Spinal Tap existed before the films\'92 productions (Nichols, 2001, p. 23). For mock-documentary\'92s 
\f1 ironic impact 
\f0 to work, it relies on the movie\'92s persuasion and the viewer\'92s belief, at least partially, that what they are watching is a documentary, because that is what the film tells the viewer they are watching (Nichols, 2001, p. 23). 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Lastly, Nichols writes about how he believes the voice of documentary is generally the voice of the oratory. The filmmaker\'92s voice takes a position concerning a feature of the historical world and tries to prove to us of its qualifications (Nichols, 2001, p. 49). To aid its 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 28 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 merits, Nichols claims that the orator must uphold the \'93three C\'92s of historical discourse: credible, convincing, and compelling\'94 (Nichols, 2001, p. 51). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Movies like 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 use the three \'92C\'92s\'91 ironically (Nichols, 2001, p. 55). The commentator seemingly establishes the film\'92s credibility. What the commentator is saying, however, is undermined by the way he says it. In the movie, for example, he treats the slaughterhouse worker as some god. With conviction, the movie purposely leaks a mocking tone masked by a seemingly objective one (Nichols, 2001, p. 55). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Nichols asks whether we can truly get a full understanding of the Hurdanos life when the commentator compares their customs to barbarian people somewhere else. 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 deliberately declines to compel truthfulness in its representation. There are clues of exaggeration which destabilize its believability. The purpose is so we can question our idiosyncrasy to accept documentary conventions and point of view as truth. 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \

\f0\fs32 \cb3 Nichols believes that irony includes not articulating with \'92what is meant,\'91or the opposite (Nichols, 2001, p. 55). The authoritative commentary in 
\f1 Land Without Bread 
\f0 is used as a hint to doubt the documentary conventions in the film. Similarly, Nichols mentions that 
\f1 Spinal Tap 
\f0 partakes in the ironic use of conventions in television journalism to suggest it is a mock- documentary. The results help the raise the audience\'92s suspicion over the films rather than validate them as legitimate representations of the world (Nichols, 2001, p. 55). 
\f1\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Critical Review 
\fs24 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 There is a lot of information regarding the history and theories surrounding mock- documentaries in the literature. On the theoretical side, Roscoe and Hight\'92s book did an excellent job of examining mock-documentary on a textual level. Both their book and Nichols\'92 literature outline how mock-documentaries work in a reflexive mode to analyze documentaries 
