\f0\fs32 \cf2 by replicating non-fiction codes. \cb3 Nichols\'92 literature also explains how mock-documentary can fit in an \cb1 industrial frame, as well as use ironic methods to share the film\'92s voice. Nichols believes that for a mock-documentary movie\'92s ironic impact (often humor or horror) to work the audience has to be willing to accept the film as documentary to some degree (Nichols, 2001, p. 23). The documentary codes that these films mimic help enforce the idea that what the viewers are watching is documentary. Roscoe and Hight go deeper in examining the different types of representations mock-documentaries present. In order to separate the different types of mock- documentaries, the authors label them with \cb3 three degrees: parody, critique and deconstruction. 
