\f0 , for example, loads the disc with secondary text to expand and continue the story. Like the film itself, the features engage with the audience ironically, as the actors -- in character \'96 look back on the experience of making the film. I argue that the reflexive use of the commentary track and an interview with the character Marty Di Bergi questions the role documentary filmmakers\'92 play when presenting themselves and their subjects. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Moving on to director Christopher Guest, he has become synonymous with his use of mock-documentary. Like Paul Verhoeven, Guest and co-writer Eugene Levy provided insight into their films through the DVDs. By looking at the multiple commentary tracks that the DVDs contain, I find that Guest uses the mock-documentary style to attempt to capture the heart and emotional levels of events and characters in his films. 
