\f0\fs32 \cf2 The only item I noticed that blatantly broke the Spinal Tap illusion on the MGM disc is a trailer found under \'93Promotional Material\'94 titled \'91Cheese Rolling Trailers.\'92 In the trailer, Rob Reiner speaks directly to the audience as himself. The biggest issue with this inclusion is everywhere else on the disc he is addressed by his character\'92s name, Di Bergi. With the trailer, Reiner says he completed his first feature film about a British rock band called Spinal Tap. The important part to note from this piece is that he never says the subject he is filming is fictional. Following his spiel about the movie, Reiner proceeds to say that he has nothing to show for it. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Instead, he presents the audience with footage he \'93found\'94 on the editing room floor and says that we might find it \'93interesting and quite informative.\'94 What follows is Reiner turning on a projector pointed at the camera as the scene transitions to some older looking film. What is shown is a short mock-documentary along the lines of a travelogue. The piece emulates documentary in what Nichols refers to as the \'93Expository Mode.\'94 In this mode, the text directly addresses the viewer with voices talking about the \'93historical world\'94 (Nichols, 1991, p.34). For the trailer, \'93old,\'94 overexposed, scratchy b-roll is shown over a poorly recorded voice over. The film depicts a fictional Scandinavian Cheese Festival where the townsfolk are rolling big wheels of cheese. According to the narrator, there were no injuries excluding \'93one spectator being crushed by runaway Gouda.\'94 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Following the clip Reiner appears on screen saying his film is nothing like this one. His movie is about rock and roll and does not contain any cheese. After examining the trailer, I find Reiner\'92s concluding statements are ironic. While it is true that both films subject matters are different, Reiner plays with Rosco and Heights first degree of mock-documentary. He uses the aesthetics to create humor for the short and the feature, albeit using different modes. Watching 
