\fs32 \cf2 The Band & Documentary Ethics 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 Moving on to the commentary, the MGM version of the DVD has the cast of 
\f1 Spinal Tap 
\f0 remarking on the film in character. Unlike the Criterion version where the commentary tells the actors experiences working on the movie, the MGM edition is a reflexive insight to the movie from the band\'92s perspective. For example, throughout the commentary they remark how Di Bergi and their producer Ian Faith (Tony Hendra) made them look stupid. For instance, in the scene at the hotel where St. Hubbins is on the phone with his girlfriend, the band mentions on the commentary track that Di Bergi carried around a secret camera. They did not know he was filming with it, and there were apparently times where Di Bergi assured them that certain pieces recorded would not make it into the film, but did. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 The commentary brings up an interesting conundrum in how the filmmakers represent the people they film. Bill Nichols points out that, in documentary, tension often arises between the filmmaker\'92s longing to make a good film and the individual wishing to keep their \'93social rights\'94 and \'93personal dignity\'94 maintained (2001, p.11). While the film does not have an answer for these complicated issues, the commentary raises the question of the director and participants\'92 role. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Throughout the film, an interview with Di Bergi and the band in front of Tufnel\'92s home is shown. It is intercut throughout the film. In the commentary track, Spinal Tap claims that Di Bergi had an agenda when he was talking to them. They say that they were not given time to prepare and believe that Di Bergi was \'93cheating\'94 because he had notes with information and answers to some of his questions. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 According to Nichols, the Interactive Mode of documentary revolves around interviews. To him, interviews are a type of \'93hierarchical discourse\'94 stemming from an \'93unequal distribution of power\'94 such as \'93confessional\'94 and interrogational (Nichols, 1991, p.47). An example from the 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 41 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 film that situates Di Bergi\'92s dominance over the band is through his lingering questions over why so many drummers in the band have died. In the commentary, the group believes he is blaming them for the accidents and is trying to get a confession that they were responsible. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Looking at the intratextual relationship between Di Bergi in the interview on the bonus features and Di Bergi in the film, we see some different characteristics. In the movie, he is very lucid and knowledgeable about his subjects. In the interview, however, he is loquacious and undignified. For instance, at one point in the interview, Di Bergi says he did not take on the project because he expected to have a lot of sex, but he did hope something \'93residual\'94 would occur (it didn\'92t). Contrast that to the Di Bergi in the film who, while having a sense of humor, seems dedicated to making a good \'93rockumentary.\'94 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 As for his sense of humor, it always seems to be at the expense of the band rather than himself. For example, during the prologue, he says that Spinal Tap is recognized for being one of London\'92s \'93loudest\'94 rock bands. He goes on to say he wanted to capture a hardworking rock band\'92s life on the road and what he got was more, \'93a lot more.\'94 After re-watching the film, his last statement comes off as mockery rather than sincerity. Looking at these two depictions of Di Bergi on the DVD, one can deduce that Di Bergi fabricated a version of himself for the movie. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Like Nichol\'92s observation of the hierarchical discourse, Di Bergi placed himself in a higher position when interacting with the band. The possible reason for the subjectivity was to exploit their unique behavior. In the interview, on the other hand, it shows that he is not as smart as the film presented him to be, and that he has not worked much in show businesses since. In fact, at the end of the interview, he tries to market himself as an experienced director to any producers that might be watching. In Di Bergi\'92s case, the filmmakers are performing a similar hierarchal operation to what he used with the band. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

