\f0\fs32 \cf2 Guest\'92s continued use and reputation with mock-documentary style is why I have selected his DVDs to analyze. Unlike the special edition of 
\f1 This is Spinal Tap
\f0 , however, the movies do not try to hide the fact of the mock-documentaries\'92 fabrication. For instance, each of the three discs has a commentary track with Guest and Levy discussing story elements and how the films were made. Along with this feature, the DVDs are embedded with \'93additional scenes\'94 as well as theatrical trailers. Despite the similarity in content, each of the extra features on the DVDs provides insight to their respective film.\uc0\u8232 
\f1 Waiting for Guffman 
\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 In 
\f1 Waiting for Guffman
\f0 , the film follows Corky St. Clair played by Guest. He is the director of a community musical production, 
\f1 Red, White, and Blaine, 
\f0 for the 150th-anniversary celebration of the fictional town of Blaine, Missouri. Corky was initially from New York and relocated to Missouri after his last play was shut down by the fire marshal. In his play that was shut down, Corky wanted the audience in the theater to have an \'93in your face\'94 experience of a fire, so he had someone burn newspapers and send the smell through the vents. Working in Missouri, he continued his unconventional way handling rehearsals and actors despite the protests from high school teacher/ musical director Lloyd Miller (Bob Balaban). The cast in the show consist of five members, Ron and Shelia Albertson (Catherine O\'92 Hara and Fred Willard), Libbe Mae Brown (Parker Posey), Dr. Allan Pearl (Levy), and Johnny Savage (Matt Keeslar). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 The Albertsons are married travel agents who enjoy performing, Brown is a young worker at Dairy Queen who seems to want to do something else with her life, and Pearl is a dentist who always wanted to become an entertainer. Lastly, Savage is a handsome but incompetent motorist who Corky convinced to be in the play. He is unenthusiastic toward it and ends up dropping out upon his father\'92s request. Corky replaces Savage\'92s part with himself. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 44 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 Corky also managed to get Clifford Wooley (Lewis Arquette), an older citizen of the town and former taxidermist, to narrate the play. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Corky along with his cast hope their musical, 
\f1 Red, White, and Blaine
\f0 , will lead to better things. Their belief is further enhanced when they learn that New York critic, Mort Guffmann, will supposedly be attending the show. Corky hopes that the play will help take him and the cast to Broadway. Everyone becomes instantly disappointed, despite the play\'92s positive reception from the town, when they learn Guffman had not shown up due a storm in New York cancelling the flight. The film is shot with mostly a \'93direct cinema\'94 style with the camera crew following Corky and the cast. Despite Guest\'92s use of documentary function, Guest rarely alludes to the purpose of the conventions on the disc.\uc0\u8232 
\f1 The Expectation for the Observer 
\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 In an interview with Virgil Bakken, Guest says he does not approach his films from an \'93intellectual basis,\'94 but rather from an emotional one (2008, p.228). His films are constructed with emotional perceptions from the beginning. This is supported in a scene from 
\f1 Guffmann 
\f0 where Corky is brooding in the bathtub. Listening to the commentary in this scene, Guest brings up the \'93documentary\'94 cameras. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 He says that when they were filming the movie he debated why the \'93camera crew\'94 would be in the bathroom when Corky clearly wants to be alone. Guest never offers an answer to why this is, but the inclusion of the camera in the bathroom suggests that Guest was focused on the emotional beats of the story rather than alerting the audience\'92s awareness to the style. A possible solution to the issue can be answered with Nichol\'92s comments on observational filmmaking. He believes the physical presence of the filmmaker should not constrain what we are able to see. Instead the audience should be placed as the \'93ideal observer\'94 (Nichols, 1991 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 45 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 p.43). In documentary, since the scenes are not invented, sometimes the filmmaker\'92s attendance becomes present, but the \'93expectation of transparent\'94 entrance remains (Nichols, 1991, p.42). In short, the \'93documentarians\'94 presence in the bathroom should not hinder the audience\'92s disbelief, because there is prospect for observational filmmaking to have an unconstrained view of the world. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Emotional Perceptions 
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 For Guest, the emotional aspect of the performer is the most crucial to attain. In all three of his mock-documentary films, almost every scene was improvised and went unrehearsed, as if the characters were in a real documentary. Levy mentions in the commentary that his character\'92s audition for Corky\'92s performance was the first time Guest had ever seen it. Guest, as Corky, had to give a response appropriate to his character. The idea behind the method was to reflect on the experiences that people go through in local theater. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Guest even said in the commentary that the rehearsal scenes with the characters served as real rehearsals for their 
\f1 Red, White, and Blaine 
\f0 performance (the only scripted part of the film). With the musical, the cast acted in front of a real group of people. According to the DVD, the extras in the crowd mainly consisted of locals from the film\'92s shooting location in Lockhart, Texas. In the commentary, Guest says that though all the cast had experience, they were still nervous to do the show. For me, the scenes in the dressing room really capture that anxiety the characters were going through to do what they believed was a huge deal. On the DVD, Guest said that the concept for 
\f1 Guffman 
\f0 originated from a junior high school performance of 
\f1 Annie Get Your Gun
\f0 . He recalls admiring the actors giving the best performances they could at their level. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Guest believes there is something charming and earnest to their devotion. With 
\f1 Guffman
\f0 , Guest said that 
\f1 Red, White, and Blaine 
\f0 had to be the most important thing in these characters\'92 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

