\f0\fs32 \cf2 An important mock-documentary titled, 
\f1 The Blair Witch Project, 
\f0 was released in 1999. The movie is significant for many reasons, such as bringing the \'93found footage\'94 mock- documentary to mainstream audiences (Heller-Nicholas, 2014, p. 87). As mentioned in the literature review, the \'93found footage\'94 subgenre is the illusion that the video was lost and uncovered (McRoy, 2004, p. 141). These mock-documentaries are meant to represent audiovisual \'93documentation\'94 of fictional events. In these films, we are told what we see is real. The ambiguous fictional position, as well as the \'93low\'94 production values, blur the borders dividing the depicted world from reality. In short, these films are not presented as an artifact, but a fragment of the \'93real\'94 world (Sayad, 2016 p. 45). 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs32 Besides the \'93found footage\'94 approach, the 
\f1 Blair Witch 
\f0 team heavily tied their marketing campaign to new media. It integrated mock-documentary aesthetics into a website to \'93sell\'94 its reality (Hopgood, 2006 p. 237). The success of the film has had a major influence on how other mock-documentary films, particularly horror \'91found footage\'91 movies, use the World Wide Web. For this chapter, I will look at several examples of mock-documentary\'92s integration into new media through original content, viral marketing, and social media. In addition to 
